<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-772-638  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 772 638.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  August 20 1990 n314 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cable decision delayed. (Regional Bell holding companies may notget permission in 1990 to enter cable television market)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Attempts by the Bell regional holding companies and othertelephone companies to obtain congressional license to enter thecable television market have been stymied by the August recess andby the fact that two proposed bills that would help their causehave been 'put on the back burner.' In order for the telephonecompanies to begin competing in the cable market, legislationwould have to be passed that would override the 1984 Cable Act,which prohibits telephone company ownership of cable televisionsystems.andP;  Telephone companies insist that if they enter the cablemarket fiber optic lines will be more readily available to homeand business users.andP;  Their competitors warn that the telephonecompanies could smother competition and use telephone revenue tofund cable enterprises.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cable TVBell Regional Holding CompaniesGovernment RegulationLegislationUnited States. CongressCompetitionTelephone CompaniesFiber Optics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>